		</table></td><td class="PanelBody" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Why cant we have a back stab?<a name="66555"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 12 04 2:52 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Just as reference, Bards 1st edition AD&amp;D.
<br />
Started as warriors.  Had to get to a set level, and not too much (between 5 and 10 I seem to recall).  Then they moved over to become a Thief class and had to get at least one more level than they did as a warrior (Max being 11), while using the AD&amp;D rules that they weren't allowed to use their old Warrior abililies (To hit tables basically).  Once they'd maxxed as a Thief, then then had to start taking tuition from a Druid, and at that point was a bard, with the ability to use all the abilites from Warrior and Rogue, while getting a sub-set of Druidic spells.  Basically a Jack of all trades, master of non.  Used to play one, took ages, and used the Unearthed Arcana rules to actually start as a Ranger (more skills such as DualWield, and Tracking), then Rogue-&gt;Acrobat, then to Bard.  Was really good fun, and started off the idea to me to be able to do a little bit of everything was more usefull usually.  Quite often the Thief in the party wasn't able to turn up for gaming night and I could substitute at least a little, then when he was there, I was added DPS.
<br />
Good fun, though heavily overpowered in many ways (starting to get hps rolls again when becoming the bard meant I started catching up with the Tanks in the party for hps again, and the Thief xp chart was so ridiculous compared to the Warrior levels at the time, I races through the rogue levels without really noticing).
<br />
2nd edition Bards were still very interesting, but lost alot of their uniqueness compared to 1st edition rules.
<br />

<br />
Sorry, old time ad&amp;d geek coming to the surface; out of curiousity, how many other people here played AD&amp;D and did it shape the characters you enjoy playing today? In many ways, EQ destroyed our gaming nights, we'd spend all night telling each other our eq adventures and not gaming.
<br />

<br />
Jyve Afk
<br />
Chaotics Neutrals have fun
<br />
Chaotic Evils have more fun</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
